**Summary:** Andrew's recognition unfolds in two moments in *Andreas* (cynewulf-andreas-07b573, ch. 1). First, after his companions describe a dream-vision of him standing before Christ as one of twelve, Andrew addresses God directly ([p-775061]): he confesses he now understands the Lord "was not far away" on the sea-path, that he could not perceive Him in the keel despite speaking many words before his Maker — and closes with praise that mercy from God is always ready for those who seek it. Then when Christ appears visibly before him ([p-ee08ea]), Andrew falls to earth and reproaches himself: he could not recognise "you so good" on the wave-path, and spoke more words before his Maker than he should have.
